>>>🛑️IP Fragmentation Process Overview
====================================

# Initial Packet (Before Fragmentation)
===============================================

	A packet (`skb`) is larger than the MTU has arrived.

	Checking for Fragmentation:
	----------------------------
	skb_has_frag_list(skb) will return `false` because it's not fragmented yet.

	The kernel enters the slow path to perform fragmentation:
	--------------------------------------------------------
	The kernel performs fragmentation and creates multiple fragments (`skb_2`, `skb_3`, etc.).

# Fragmentation Process
===============================

	After fragmentation:
	--------------------
	- `skb->frag_list` points to the first fragment (`skb_2`).
	- `skb_2->next` points to the next fragment (`skb_3`), and so on.

	The kernel processes the entire chain of fragments:
	---------------------------------------------------
	The kernel follows the fast path for the fragments once the packet is fragmented.

	Using `nr_frags` for Processing:
	-------------------------------
	The kernel will use the `nr_frags` value to know how many fragments it needs to process for this packet.

# Processing Fragments
=========================

	Once fragmented, the kernel processes each fragment:
	----------------------------------------
	- Process `skb_2`, `skb_3`, etc., one by one.
	- The kernel does not re-fragment `skb_2` or `skb_3`; instead, it processes them directly as part of the same fragmented packet.

	No re-fragmentation occurs:
	---------------------------
	The fragments are processed as part of the same original packet. No additional fragmentation takes place.

# Next Packet (New Fragmentation)
==================================

	For a different packet that needs fragmentation:
	-----------------------------------------------
	If a new packet (not part of the original chain) is too large, it will go through the same process:
	- `skb_has_frag_list(new_skb)` will return `false` for the new packet.
	- The kernel will enter the slow path and fragment the new packet.

	Once the new packet is fragmented:
	-----------------------------------
	After fragmentation, the kernel follows the fast path for the fragments of that packet.

	Processing the new fragments:
	-----------------------------
	The kernel follows the same procedure to process the fragments of the new packet:
	- Process `new_skb_2`, `new_skb_3`, etc., as part of the new fragmented packet.
