BELOW IS THE DETAILED THING ABOUT SLOW PATH AND FAST PATH
=============================================================================

>>DIFFERENCES:
-----------------

| Operation                                        | Slow Path | Fast Path                                      |
| ------------------------------------------------ | --------- | ---------------------------------------------  |
| Allocate new SKBs (`alloc_skb()`)                | ✔         | ❌                                             |
| Reserve link-layer space (`skb_reserve()`)       | ✔         | ❌                                             |
| Add header+payload space (`skb_put()`)           | ✔         | ❌                                             |
| Copy IPv4 header (`skb_copy_from_linear_data()`) | ✔         | ❌**(copies header only from first fragment)** |
| Copy payload (`skb_copy_bits()`)                 | ✔         | ❌                                             |
| Rebuild fragments from scratch                   | ✔         | ❌                                             |



>>WHAT FAST PATH DOES: 
----------------------

| Operation                                 | Fast Path                 |
| ----------------------------------------- | ------------------------- |
| Copies the IPv4 header onto each fragment | ✔ *(but no payload copy)* |
| Adjusts fragment offsets                  | ✔                         |
| Sets MF flag                              | ✔                         |
| Updates tot_len                           | ✔                         |
| Recalculates checksum                     | ✔                         |
| Sends the fragment                        | ✔                         |


===============================================
          SLOW PATH FRAGMENTATION (IPv4)
===============================================

1. SETUP
   - Extract IPv4 header:
       iph = ip_hdr(skb)
   - Determine remaining payload:
       left = skb->len - hlen

2. LOOP WHILE DATA REMAINS
   while (left > 0)

3. CALCULATE FRAGMENT SIZE
   - Start with remaining data:
       len = left
   - Limit to MTU:
       if (len > mtu)
           len = mtu
   - Align to 8-byte boundary (except last fragment):
       len &= ~7

4. ALLOCATE NEW SKB FOR FRAGMENT
   - Allocate buffer:
       skb2 = alloc_skb(len + hlen + ll_rs)
   - If allocation fails:
       return -ENOMEM

5. COPY METADATA FROM ORIGINAL PACKET
   - Copy pkt_type, priority, protocol, etc.:
       ip_copy_metadata(skb2, skb)

6. RESERVE SPACE AND PUT DATA
   - Reserve link-layer header space:
       skb_reserve(skb2, ll_rs)
   - Mark header + payload area as valid:
       skb_put(skb2, len + hlen)
   - Set network header pointer:
       skb_reset_network_header(skb2)

7. COPY IP HEADER
   - Copy original IP header into fragment:
       skb_copy_from_linear_data(skb, skb_network_header(skb2), hlen)

8. COPY PAYLOAD DATA
   - Copy 'len' bytes from original packet:
       skb_copy_bits(skb, ptr, skb_transport_header(skb2), len)
   - Reduce remaining data:
       left -= len

9. SET FRAGMENT OFFSET
   - Offset measured in 8-byte units:
       iph->frag_off = htons(offset >> 3)

10. HANDLE OPTIONS ONLY ON FIRST FRAGMENT
   if (offset == 0)
       ip_options_fragment(skb)

11. SET IP_MF FLAG IF MORE FRAGMENTS FOLLOW
   if (left > 0 || not_last_frag)
       iph->frag_off |= htons(IP_MF)

12. UPDATE POINTERS
   ptr    += len
   offset += len

13. SET TOTAL LENGTH AND RECOMPUTE CHECKSUM
   iph->tot_len = htons(len + hlen)
   ip_send_check(iph)

14. SEND THE FRAGMENT
   err = output(skb2)
   if (err) {
       free buffers
       increment IPSTATS_MIB_FRAGFAILS
       return err
   }
   IP_INC_STATS(... FRAGCREATES)

